    <p class="lead">This guide will introduce you to RefineryCMS and set out the standards and conventions that we use for our various About, Help and Information pages, including how we make our pages both responsive and accessible.</p>
    <p><strong>Responsive</strong> pages look good on any device, of any width, from a large desktop computer down to a mobile phone. Our pages must also be <strong>accessible</strong> to all users, including those who use screen readers, those with motor issues who cannot use a pointing device, those with cognitive issues who need clear, concise content and a whole raft of other users who deserve special consideration.</p>
    
    <p>If you have some familiarity with HTML, you will find enough information here to mark up most, if not all, of a page. Do as much as you can and do not worry if you feel you have reached your limit before completing the page.</p>
    <p>If you are <strong>new to using HTML</strong>, take things slowly and do the easy bits first — paragraphs and headings. Ask for help as often as you need to and leave the layout and menus to someone more experienced — unless you are feeling brave!</p>
    <p>Do not be put off by the length of this Guide — it turns out that it is much easier to <em>do</em> some things than it is to <em>explain how</em> to do them. Nevertheless, please read (or skim!) the whole guide <em>before</em> you begin marking up — it could save you some work in the long run. In particular, if you are going to be marking up the layout, please read the section on <a href="#layout">Page layout and sub-menus</a> before adding the page text.</p>
    <p id="copyMarkup" class="island island--bordered"><strong>Copy the lines of example markup</strong> on this page from the browser window, <em>not</em> the HTML source, which is mainly entities, i.e. references to characters, such as the left angle bracket, <code>&amp;lt;</code>. (You probably realised that, but it’s worth saying anyway!)</p>
