    <p>Our pages use HTML5 (Hypertext Markup Language version 5) — see the <a href="https://www.w3schools.com/html/default.asp">HTML5 tutorial at w3c schools</a> or their <a href="https://www.w3schools.com/tags/default.asp">HTML reference</a>. The character set is UTF-8 (8-bit Unicode Transformation Format).</p>

    <p>The house styling for our pages is built into our CSS (cascading style sheets). Fonts, colours, alignment, and spacing, for example, are all set up for you. Do not attempt to override our styles — if you believe that something different is needed, please seek advice.</p>
    <p>We use CSS classes instead of some of the attributes common in earlier versions of HTML — especially those attributes that are deprecated (i.e. obsolete, superseded and to be avoided) in HTML5.</p>
    <hr class="rule rule--ornament" />

    <h2 id="refineryIntro">Using RefineryCMS</h2>
    <p>RefineryCMS is a so-called content management system (CMS). Although that term sounds impressive, please bear in mind that as it stands, Refinery is a pretty simple affair. If you need to do a complex bit of editing, such as a widespread search-and-replace, you will want to temporarily copy the page (from the HTML pane) to a decent text-editor, make the changes and then paste it back into Refinery (into the HTML pane). To avoid someone else editing the Refinery page in the resulting interval, please leave a brief note at the top of the page — the <code>mark</code> element is useful for this as it places a yellow highlight under your words which is visible in the Refinery preview pane.</p>
    <p>If you do not have a decent text-editor, there are some suggestions in <a href="#resources">Resources, below</a>. There are also links to a few online tools that will help you fix indentation, find unclosed elements and validate your HTML.</p>
    <p>The content you create in Refinery will be placed immediately after the page <code>h1</code> heading (see <a href="#fig1">figure&#160;1, label&#160;2, above</a> and <a href="#headings">Headings, below</a>). It will end just before the footer (or just before the ‘Top of page’ and ‘Report a problem’ buttons if you are logged-in).</p>
    <p>Place all content in the ‘Body’ tab, which is open by default. We do not use the tab labelled ‘Side body’. See fig. 2:</p>

    
