    <h3 id="semantic">Semantic markup</h3>
    <p>If you find you have styled a piece of text to look like a heading, ask yourself whether it <em>is</em> a heading. If the answer is yes, then mark it up as a heading. This will help screen reader users to understand the structure of the page because all headings are included in a list that they can hear and use to navigate the page.</p>
    <p>Headings also help sighted users to find specific information and understand what is available on a page: in other words, headings help all users.</p>
    <p class="push-half--bottom">Semantic markup enables screen reader software to interpret the page content correctly for a user: it’s one of the ways we make our pages accessible to all users, including volunteers, despite any limitations they might have. Other important considerations include:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>markup should be valid (in HTML5) — for more information and a link to a validator, see <a href="#resources">Resources, below</a> </li>
      <li>we cannot bury information in <code>title</code> attributes — users who do not (or cannot) use a pointing device will never see the contents, so do not use them and delete any that Refinery inserts</li>
    </ul>
    <p>We use lower-case for element tags — <code>h2</code>, not H2 — and for <code>id</code> (identifier) names. For an <code>id</code> that is really more than one word, we use camelCase (sic). For example <code>id="nextSteps"</code>.</p>
    <hr class="rule" />

    <h3 id="leadPara">The opening paragraph</h3>
    <p>Make sure the page has a suitable opening paragraph: it should describe what the page is about without going into the details. Give it the class <code>lead</code>.</p>
    <hr class="rule rule--ornament" />

    <h3 id="headings">Headings</h3>
    <p>The main page heading, the <code>h1</code> element, is created by Refinery from the contents of the Refinery ‘Title’ field — the box immediately above the ‘Body’ tab (see <a href="#fig2">figure 2, above</a>). In other words, do <strong>not</strong> mark up an h1-heading yourself.</p>
    <p>Please ensure that all headings use <em>sentence case</em>, that is use capital letters exactly as if the words are the beginning of a sentence in a paragraph: “Marking up pages in Refinery”, “The FreeBMD project”, “Frequently asked questions”.</p> 
    <p>Refinery generates the HTML file-name by converting this page ‘Title’ to lower-case, removing the punctuation and replacing spaces with hyphens. (Which means that you can change the casing of a page ‘Title’ without breaking incoming links.)</p>
    <p class="islet islet--navy">On FreeREG, the Refinery ‘Title’ is also part of the (proper!) <code>title</code> element in the page <code>head</code>. The set-up is being adopted gradually for FreeBMD and FreeCEN.</p>
    <p><strong>Please note</strong> that only one of the fields in ‘Toggle advanced options’, at the foot of the Refinery screen, has any effect on your page: leave ‘Display this page in the site menu’ checked (to prevent the page becoming hidden). Leave the other fields empty or unchecked.</p>
    <p>Use the <code>h2</code> element for headings for the main sections of the page: give each <code>h2</code> element an <code>id</code>, to be used for the page sub-menu and for other in-page links. Shorter names are easier to deal with, provided they are meaningful: for example,  <code>id="contentMarkup"</code> is simpler than <code>id="markingUpPageContent"</code>. (Please note that anchor elements with a name attribute are not valid in HTML5.)</p>
    <p>If a section needs a sub-heading, then use <code>h3</code>. A sub-subheading would be <code>h4</code>, and so on. Ensure headings follow this proper hierarchy as this supplies important information about the structure of the page content, both visually and for screen reader users.</p>
    <hr class="rule rule--ornament" />
    
    <h3 id="links">Links</h3>
    <p>Please ensure that link-text is <strong>meaningful</strong>: never use ‘here’ or ‘described above’ or similar as link-text. A link should be easy to find and identify in a list of links.</p>
    <p>Do not use the same link-text for links that have different destinations; similarly, links to exactly the same destination should have the same link-text.</p>
    <p>If the page and/or section does not exist yet, or exists only as a draft, insert the link in Markdown-style for now: <code>[link-text](name of draft page)</code>, replacing ‘link-text’ with the appropriate, meaningful words (for screen reader users especially, the link-text should be easy to understand and the destination clear, without the context of the surrounding text.)</p>
    <p>The easiest way to make a <strong>link to another Refinery page</strong> is to type the link-text and then work in the preview pane. Select your link-text and then select the ‘Add link’ button. From the list of categories, choose ‘Your page’ and then find the page that you want from the list that will appear on the right. Select that page and then select ‘Insert’. Finally, if you are linking to a particular part of a page, open the HTML pane and append a hash (#) and the id of that section. (Remember to remove the <code>title</code> attribute added to the link by Refinery.)</p>
    <p>If you look in the HTML pane you’ll see that the link address begins with a forward slash (/). This stands for the root of a site (the current domain name) and is the way to ensure that a page on for example, <em>test3.freebmd.org.uk</em> can be transferred to plain <em>freebmd.org.uk</em> without breaking the link. A page created in Refinery will have an address that begins with ‘/cms/’.</p>
    
    <h4>Links that open in a new tab</h4>
    <p>Links that open in a new browser tab (or window), using the attribute <code>target="_blank"</code>, should be used sparingly, and <em>only</em> as agreed in a Scrum. A user can always choose to open a link in a new tab or window, by way of the context menu, but they cannot override a target attribute in the markup.</p>
    <p>The target attribute can be set automatically by working in the Preview pane and using ‘Insert link’, choosing ‘Website’ and then checking the ‘New window’ box. We must add ‘ (opens in new tab)’ to the link-text because opening in a new tab can be confusing if the user does not expect it. (The browser default is to open such a link in a new tab rather than a new window: Refinery is out of date.)</p>
    
    <h4>Links to documents</h4>
    <p>We should also warn users, as part of the link-text, where a link is to anything other than an HTML page: for example, ‘how to herd cats (PDF, 1.8MB)’.</p>
    <p>You might be tempted to include a <strong>title attribute</strong> in the opening <code>a</code> tag. However, be aware that not all users will be able to see the contents of a title attribute — sighted keyboard-only users will never know it’s there. We cannot bury new information in a <code>title</code> attribute, so do not use it.</p>
    <p class="islet islet--bordered"><strong>NB:</strong> some of the advice in the following paragraph might have to change if I cannot convince a developer — and the SCRUM — that the automatic <code>id</code> described is needed, or at least desirable.</p>
    <p>For a <strong>Top of page</strong> link, you can use <code>href="#top"</code> on CEN and REG. An element with <code>id="top"</code> is automatically part of all pages on CEN and REG but we are still awaiting one on BMD. Do not use <code>href="#"</code> as it is not a valid address and will cause problems for keyboard-only users (as will a link to a non-existent or repeated <code>id</code> (identifier) name). The issue is that the browser window will move to the top of the page, but the focus will <em>not</em> move: the next press of the tab key will take the user to the next link <em>after</em> where they started!</p>
    
    <h4>Better link-text</h4>
    <p>The following examples would all send a user to this address: <code>href="/cms/advanced-user-guide#wildcards"</code>. (The example links are false, so do not try to follow them!)</p>
    <p>An example of a less helpful link:<br /> 
      “Our <a href="cms/advanced-user-guide#wildcards">advanced user guide</a> covers wildcard searches” <br /> This is less helpful because important information about the destination is placed after the link, where a screen reader user could miss it, having already followed the link.</p>
    <p>An example of a better link:<br /> “We cover searching using wildcards in our <a href="cms/advanced-user-guide#wildcards">advanced user guide</a>” <br />This is better because the information about the destination comes before the link.</p>
    <p>An example of an even better link:<br /> “We cover <a href="cms/advanced-user-guide#wildcards">searching using wildcards in our advanced user guide</a>”<br />This is even better because the information is part of the link-text itself, making it easy to distinguish this link from others that point to different sections of the advanced user guide. (“We cover” does not add anything, so it is not part of the link-text.)</p>
    <hr class="rule rule--ornament" />

    <h3 id="email">Email addresses</h3>
    <p>In general, we do not publish email addresses. If an email address seems essential, please ask your manager for advice.</p>
    <hr class="rule rule--ornament" />

    <h3 id="tables">Tables</h3>
    <p>For each table that you plan to use, ask yourself, does this information really belong in a table? Is it really a list in disguise? Is it really something else entirely? Please note that we do not use tables to achieve any sort of layout. A table would not be meaningful as a way of merely setting out some information neatly — it’s not semantic.</p>
    <p>If the data really is tabular, use the <code>thead</code> and <code>tbody</code> elements, as appropriate. Mark up any column headings with <code>th scope="col"</code> and any row headings with <code>th scope="row"</code> rather than a plain <code>td</code>.</p>
    <p>Remove attributes such as <code>border</code>, for example. Make sure you are happy with how it looks on a mobile-width screen. In addition, a table should have a brief <code>caption</code> element (as its first child) that explains the structure of the table. You can make the caption invisible to all but screen reader users, if that is appropriate, by using <code>class="accessibility"</code>.</p>
    <p>If the default table styling does not work for your particular table, please ask for advice.</p>
    <p class="push-half--bottom">This is the full markup for a basic table that has both column and row headings. It also has the numbers aligned to the right which makes it easier to appreciate their relative size:</p>
