    <h3 id="abbrDfn">Abbreviations and definitions</h3>
    <p>The <code>abbr</code> element is not accessible to a sighted, keyboard-only user (because they cannot hover), so do not use it. Similarly, the <code>dfn</code> element relies on a user’s ability to hover, so do not use that.</p>
    <p>Explain an abbreviation the first time it’s used on a page. For example, “the General Registration Office (the G.R.O.)”. In this case we put full stops after the letters to prevent a screen reader announcing, ‘the grow’. Similarly, use ‘T.W.Y.S’. because ‘TWYS’ is voiced as ‘twise’; use ‘I.C.O.’ because ‘ICO’ is voiced as ‘eye co’.</p>
    <p>There may well be other abbreviations which need a similar treatment. They will be listed here as they come to light.</p>
    <p>Use the word Microsoft rather than the abbreviation MS which is voiced as ‘mz’</p>
    <p><strong>URL</strong> is voiced correctly; for the plural use URL’s.</p>
    <p><strong>FAQ</strong> is voiced correctly (and helpfully) as ‘frequently asked questions’; FAQs is voiced as ‘F A queues’ which is less easy to understand for some users.</p>
    <p>The term <strong>UserID</strong> is voiced correctly whereas all the other variations tested failed. Yes, this is one for Member’s pages, but not all volunteers need to be able to see! It is simply good policy (and good manners) to make members’ pages accessible where it is easy do so.</p>
    <p>It seems that ‘ID’ by itself (and however cased) is voiced as the single syllable ‘id’. So, should you need the term, type ‘id (i.e. identifier)’. Do not type ‘I.D.’ or ‘i.d.’ which make no sense as abbreviations. (The identifier attribute is typed ‘<code>id</code>’ in this document.)</p>
    <hr class="rule rule--ornament" />

    <h3 id="lists">Lists</h3>
    <p>There are three kinds of list in HTML5: the unordered list, <code>ul</code>, which uses bullets; the ordered list, <code>ol</code>, which is numbered (or otherwise ordered); and the description list, <code>dl</code> (formerly known as the definition list). A description list typically consists of pairs of terms, <code>dt</code>, with their descriptions, <code>dd</code>.</p>
    <p>List-items (<code>li</code>s) must have a parent container, either a <code>ul</code> or an <code>ol</code>, whichever is more appropriate.</p>
    <p class="push-half--bottom">In addition, every list item should begin with a lower-case letter (unless the word is a proper noun, such as England or Refinery) and not have any end-of-item (or end-of-list) punctuation:</p>    
    <ul>
      <li class="dont">Not like this;</li>
      <li class="do">like this</li>
    </ul>

    <p>Give the paragraph that introduces the list the class <code>push-half--bottom</code>, which will bring it a little closer to the list. The significance of the punctuation in the class name is explained below in <a href="#cssClassNames">CSS class names</a>.</p>
    <p>You can use either of the first two list types out-of-the-box, but a plain description list may need some tweaking! We have some useful styles available, but they currently need setting up on a page-by-page basis — please let our HTML and CSS person know what you have in mind and they will perform the magic. (We also have some styles for particular uses that are fully defined in our CSS, but their use is beyond the scope of this Guide.)</p>
    <hr class="rule rule--ornament" />

    <h3 id="emphasis">Adding emphasis</h3>

    <p>Any text in upper-case should be replaced with sentence-case words. This is because WORDS IN CAPITAL LETTERS ARE MORE DIFFICULT TO READ and could be taken as shouting. Instead, use <code>em</code> elements or <code>strong</code> elements (tip: Refinery will convert <code>b</code> elements to <code>strong</code> on saving).</p>

    <p>To call out an important block of text, use either an <code>islet</code> or an <code>island</code> class. The main difference is in the amount of space (padding) around the text: an island has more padding than an islet. You can set a border or a background-colour using one of our CSS modifier classes. These examples show just a few of the possible combinations:</p>
    <div class="island">
      I am a plain island: use <code>class="island"</code>
    </div>
    <div class="islet islet--light">
      I am a light islet: use <code>class="islet islet--light"</code>
    </div>
    <div class="island island--bordered">
      I am a bordered island: use <code>class="island island--bordered"</code>
    </div>
    <div class="islet islet--neutral">
      I am a neutral islet: use <code>class="islet islet--neutral"</code>
    </div>
    <div class="islet islet--neutral">
      <p>I am a neutral islet with text in a <code>p</code> element: this makes the text size smaller than our default</p>
    </div>
    <div class="island island--dark">
      I am a dark island: use <code>class="island island--dark"</code>
    </div>
    <p>Our white-text-on-dark styles are: <code>--dark</code>, <code>--navy</code>, <code>--teal</code>, <code>--turquoise</code>, <code>--lavender</code>, and <code>--magenta</code>. In order not to confuse or annoy a user, please do <strong>not</strong> use your project’s link and button colour. (You can use each modifier class, for colour or border, with either an islet or island prefix, as appropriate.)</p>
    <p>Note that link styling will be adjusted automatically, if necessary (to maintain good colour contrast), for all islets and islands.</p>

    <p>You can read about what the double-hyphens and double-underscores signify, below in <a href="#cssClassNames">CSS class names</a>.</p>
    <hr class="rule rule--ornament" />

    <h3 id="quotes">Quotation marks and apostrophes</h3>

    <p>Please do not use the keyboard quotation marks or the <code>&amp;quot;</code> entity — they are ugly.</p>

    <p>We add a pair of curly (or typographers), single quotation marks using the left and right single quote entities: <code>&amp;lsquo;Body&amp;rsquo;</code> gives, ‘Body’.</p> 
    <p>Similarly, to add a pair of curly (or typographers), double quotation marks, use the left and right double quote entities: <code>&amp;ldquo;Body&amp;rdquo;</code> gives, “Body”.</p>
     
    <p>The <code>q</code> and <code>blockquote</code> elements are only for quotations from another source and should not be used merely to get quotation marks.</p>

    <p>For an <strong>apostrophe</strong>, use the right single-quote entity, <code>&amp;rsquo;</code>.  Please do not use the keyboard single quotation mark or the apostrophe entity – Internet Explorer does not understand it. Note that the W3C (the World Wide Web Consortium), the Unicode standard and <em>A List Apart</em> all favour using the right single quote for an apostrophe.</p>
    <p class="push-half--bottom">A visual guide to quotation-marks:</p>
    <ul>
      <li class="dont">keyboard left (and right) single-quotes — ' '</li>
      <li class="dont">keyboard left (and right) double-quotes — " "</li>
      <li class="do">left and right single-quotes, entity names — <code>&amp;lsquo; &amp;rsquo;</code> — ‘  ’</li>
      <li class="do">left and right single-quotes, entity numbers <code>&amp;#8216; &amp;#8217;</code> — ‘ ’</li>
      <li class="do">left and right double-quotes, entity names — <code>&amp;ldquo; &amp;rdquo;</code> — “ ”</li>
      <li class="do">left and right double-quotes, entity numbers — <code>&amp;#8220; &amp;#8221;</code> —  “ ”</li>
    </ul>
    <hr class="rule rule--ornament" />

    <h3 id="entitiesHyphensDashes">Entities, hyphens &amp; dashes</h3>

    <p>On saving, Refinery will replace some entities with their UTF-8 character. This can be helpful or not, depending on how you like to work.</p>
    <p>Please use the <strong>non-breaking space</strong>, <code>&amp;nbsp;</code> or <code>&amp;#160;</code>, sparingly and appropriately. It is useful, for example, to stop a name or a date from breaking across two lines. It should never be used in an attempt to control spacing or indentation or even alignment: it simply will not work (at all window widths and on all browsers). Please be aware that if you paste text into the Refinery preview pane, you could have to remove a bunch of non-breaking spaces, especially if the typist is in the habit of placing two spaces after a full stop.</p>
    <p>Please ensure that <strong>hyphens</strong> (-) are used only to hyphenate words: for example, link-text or search-and-replace. Some words work better for a screen reader where hyphenated. For example, wild card or wild-card rather than wildcard; off-line rather than offline. Refinery will not save a non-breaking hyphen (&amp;#8209;) — it will crash.</p>
    <p>The longer <strong>em-dash</strong>, <code>&amp;mdash;</code> or <code>&amp;#8212;</code> (—), is the dash of running text. Put a space either side of the em-dash. Mac users can insert a UTF-8 em-dash with <kbd>shift</kbd> + <kbd>option</kbd> + <kbd>-</kbd> (a hyphen).</p>
    <p>The shorter en-dash, <code>&amp;ndash;</code> or <code>&amp;#8211</code> is used to separate a range of numbers: 18–32. No space between a number and the en-dash. However, a screen reader user might not know that it is there, so instead of ‘18–32’, it is better to say ‘18 to 32’.</p>
    <p>Please use a horizontal ellipsis, <code>&amp;hellip;</code> or <code>&amp;#8230;</code> (the … symbol), rather than three full stops (...): it is the correct (single) character and the spacing is consistently better. Mac users can use <kbd>option</kbd> + <kbd>;</kbd> (a semicolon) to insert a (UTF-8) horizontal ellipsis.</p>
    <h4>Caution</h4>
    <p>There are some entities that Refinery will not save — the more common ones are the vertical ellipsis, arrows, the minus sign, the non-breaking hyphen and letters of the Greek alphabet (as far as I know!).</p>
    
    <h3 id="specialWords">Words and abbreviations that need special treatment</h3>
    
    <p>Some words that are not considered to be good, every-day English need to written as they would be found in a dictionary. Otherwise they will be mis-pronounced by screen readers, sometimes to the point of being unrecognisable.</p>
    <table>
      <caption>Words that need special treatment</caption>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th class="do" scope="col">Use</th>
          <th class="dont" scope="col">Do not use</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>wild card or wild-card</td>
          <td>wildcard</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>off line or off-line</td>
          <td>offline</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <table>
      <caption>Abbreviations that need special treatment</caption>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th class="do" scope="col">Use</th>
          <th class="dont" scope="col">Do not use</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>T.W.Y.S.</td>
          <td>TWYS</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>I.C.O.</td>
          <td>ICO</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>G.R.O.</td>
          <td>GRO</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Microsoft</td>
          <td>MS</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>URL’s &amp; PURL’s</td>
          <td>URLs &amp; PURLs (plural)</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <p>Some abbreviations that are (probably) expanded by a screen reader include FAQ (frequently asked questions), e.g. (for example), i.e. (that is). However, please remember those sighted users who do not know what these abbreviations stand for.</p>
    <hr class="rule rule--ornament" />

    <h3 id="rules">Horizontal rules</h3>

    <p>The horizontal rule, <code>hr</code>, is useful for marking a change in topic. The browser default is a bit clunky, so please give it the class, <code>rule</code>. You can mark a more emphatic break by adding a second class, <code>class="rule rule--ornament"</code>.</p>
    <p class="island island--dark">Note that the class <code>rule--ornament</code> is currently missing from the CSS of FreeBMD</p>

    <hr class="rule rule--ornament" />

    <h2 id="images">Adding images</h2>

    <p>Images used in Refinery pages should be relevant, focussed (with no extraneous clutter) and otherwise of good quality. A good image is worth the proverbial ‘thousand words’, but a poor one is horribly distracting.</p>
    <p>Images come in many sizes and it is impossible to cover every situation here.</p>
    <p>When creating an image intended for a Refinery page, consider the size it will be displayed at. On a wide screen, that will be about 700px, the maximum width of the wider, left column (minus the margins). A PNG (portable network graphic) image that is no wider than about 1100px will generally scale well on our pages. But do check that any text in the image that you want a user to be able to read, is still legible at a <em>window</em> width of 1024px.</p>
    <p>In any case, every image should have an <code>alt</code> attribute with a <em>brief</em> description of the image, including any text in that image. A full description, including a transcription of any relevant writing should be given in the page text so that it is accessible to all users, whatever their eyesight, and not only to screen reader users.</p>
    <p>As ever, if you run into problems, ask for advice.</p>
    <p>You can assume that pages intended for members only will be viewed on larger screens. As above, reduce your <em>window</em> width to about 1100px before you take the screen-shot. Yes, we can allow an image to fill the full width of a Refinery page, but we wouldn’t want to do so routinely as that would complicate the page layout, making it much easier to break with future edits or updates.</p>
    <p>If you want to <strong>annotate</strong> the screen-shot — to draw attention to a button, say —  please save a backup copy of the plain image first. Then annotate or highlight using suitable tools rather than freehand squiggles.</p>
    <p>An image should have a <strong>caption</strong> (the <code>figcaption</code> element): we cannot rely on a <code>title</code> attribute being accessible to all — users on mobile devices and sighted, keyboard-only users will never see it. The caption should be informative yet as brief as is appropriate, with no redundant words such as ‘this shows’  — even a screen reader user will know that the caption is describing an image.</p>
    <p>The markup for an image with a caption uses the <code>figure</code> element. The block below is indented four spaces (which is likely what you will need) for convenience:</p>
    <pre>    &lt;figure&gt;
      &lt;img url="…" alt="…" width="…" height="…"&gt;
      &lt;figcaption&gt;…&lt;/figcaption&gt;
    &lt;/figure&gt;
    </pre>

    <p>The <code>figure</code> element groups the image with its caption and allows screen reader software to know that the two belong together. It also makes it simple to apply a border to a screen-shot (to help a user distinguish the image from interactive page content). Currently, the style is applied on a page-by-page basis: in the future you will be able to simply use a class.</p>
    <p>The <code>alt</code> attribute is displayed if the image becomes unavailable for any reason — it will also be read to a screen reader user. There should be no need for a <code>title</code> attribute for an image — contrary to popular belief, it does nothing to improve accessibility. Unfortunately, Refinery insists on inserting one: please delete the <code>title</code> attribute so that screen reader users are not irritated by hearing the contents of both a <code>title</code> attribute <em>and</em> an <code>alt</code> attribute.</p>
    <hr class="rule" />
    
    <h3>Uploading images</h3>
    <p>You cannot place an image in a Refinery page unless you or someone else uploads it to Refinery: the upload and placement <em>can</em> be done together, but you might lose the original width and height values. Be kind to other volunteers who check and edit pages by uploading the image first and inserting it later.</p>
    <p>To upload an image, select the Images button from the left-hand menu, then select ‘Add new image’. You can choose to specify the <code>alt</code> text, but you must then also specify the <code>title</code> text, even though you will delete the latter after adding the image to the page. If you do not specify the <code>title</code> text, Refinery will not save your <code>alt</code> text. If you leave the options blank, Refinery will save an adapted version of the file name.</p>
    <p>Accidents happen, so please keep a copy of any image that you upload to Refinery: if you have annotated the image, please keep a copy of that and a copy of the unannotated image. Please upload copies of your final images, including all significant versions of those images, to the appropriate folder on the Google Drive — please ask your manager for details.</p>
    <hr class="rule" />

    <h3>Inserting an image</h3>
    <p>Close the HTML pane and place the cursor in the preview pane at the place you want the image to be. Select ‘Insert image’. Choose the image you need from the listing. Uncheck ‘Resize image’. Select ‘Insert’.</p>
    <p>Now open the HTML pane. Check that the <code>img</code> element has landed in the right place and move it if not. Then check the <code>img</code> attributes and adjust as necessary (for example, delete the <code>title</code> attribute and ensure that the <code>alt</code> attribute is short and sweet — in particular, it should not be a straight repeat of the caption).</p>
    <p class="island island--bordered">It is possible to insert an image with the HTML pane open, but you could find things easier with the pane closed. Do whatever suits your way of working.</p>
   <p>If your image does not display as you intended and simple trouble-shooting does not fix it, please ask for advice.</p>
    <hr class="rule rule--ornament" />

