    <h3 id="structure">Adding structure</h3>
    <p class="push-half--bottom">Setting up the page layout and adding any sub-menus is only a little more involved than marking up the content:</p>
    <ol>
      <li>copy and paste the lines for the layout, given below</li>
      <li>then add your content to the wider (three-fifths) column and polish</li>
      <li>copy and paste the lines for a sub-menu, below, into the narrower (two-fifths) column, then edit the link-text and <code>id</code> names for your page</li>
    </ol>
    <p>A basic layout for a simple help or information page is given below. It can be adapted to fit unusual page contents, but please use the following as your starting point:</p>
    <pre>&lt;div class="grid"&gt;
  &lt;div class="grid__item three-fifths lap-two-thirds palm-one-whole"&gt;
    &lt;p class="lead"&gt; … &lt;/p&gt;
    &lt;p&gt; *other introductory material &lt;/p&gt;
  &lt;/div&gt;
  &lt;div class="grid__item two-fifths lap-one-third palm-one-whole float--right"&gt;
    *sub-menus go here*
  &lt;/div&gt;
  &lt;div class="grid__item three-fifths lap-two-thirds palm-one-whole"&gt;
    *page main content goes here*
  &lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
    </pre>
    <p>More complex page layouts are possible (if required) but they are beyond the scope of this Guide. You will also come across pages that do not have this layout pattern, but that is either because the page is different in some way, or because it is older than average and has not been updated recently.</p>
    <hr class="rule" />

    <h3 id="subMenus">Adding sub-menus</h3>
    <p>A page typically has two sub-menus: ‘On this page’, plus a listing of the other pages in the same set of Help, About or Information pages.</p>

    <p>Please mark up an ‘On this page’ sub-menu like this, editing the list items (the <code>href</code> attributes and the link-text) for your page:</p>
    <pre>    &lt;nav aria-labelledby="thisPage"&gt;
      &lt;div class="islet islet--bordered"&gt;
        &lt;h2 class="title-block" id="thisPage"&gt;On this page&lt;/h2&gt;
        &lt;ul class="sub-nav"&gt;
          &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="#firstSection"&gt;First section&lt;/a&gt; &lt;/li&gt;
          &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="#nextSection"&gt;Next part&lt;/a&gt; &lt;/li&gt;
          &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="#thirdPart"&gt;And so on&lt;/a&gt; &lt;/li&gt;
        &lt;/ul&gt;
      &lt;/div&gt;
    &lt;/nav&gt;
    </pre>
    <p>The sub-menu is an unordered list, with the class <code>sub-nav</code>. The heading is an <code>h2</code> element with the class <code>title-block</code>.</p>
    <p>In a list available to screen reader users, the navigation block will be labelled “On this page” to distinguish it from other navigation blocks on the page.</p>
    <div class="islet islet--navy">
      <p>We believe we have now fixed the Refinery issue that removed the ARIA label. If you want to see and hear your label in action, try learning the basics of how to use a screen reader: Narrator is bundled on a PC, VoiceOver on a Mac.</p>
      <p>There is more about ‘aria-labelledby’ in <a href="#waiAria">WAI-ARIA, below</a>.</p>
    </div>
    <p>The list items for the ‘On this page’ sub-menu are typically the second-level headings used in the page.</p>
    
    <p>For a list of related pages, or pages in the same grouping, the principle is the same. Replace the <code>nav</code> element with an <code>aside</code> element. Adjust the heading to suit. If you add a sub-menu of pages from the same group as the current page, then include the current page, giving its <code>li</code> the class <code>active</code>. Please add ‘ (this page)’ to the link-text.</p>
    <p class="islet islet--bordered">Please note that if the ‘On this page’ menu is a long one, it could work better to place a list of related pages further down the page. Ask your manager for advice.</p>
    
    <p><strong>What if you need a nested sub-menu?</strong> Say that one of the sections (h2) has important sub-sections (h3) that should be easy to find. The following markup will give you a good-looking, nested menu:</p>
    <pre>  &lt;div class="islet islet--bordered"&gt;
    &lt;h2 class="title-block" id="thisPage"&gt;On this page&lt;/h2&gt;
    &lt;ul class="sub-nav"&gt;
      &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="#firstSection"&gt;…&lt;/a&gt; &lt;/li&gt;
      &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="#nextSection"&gt;…&lt;/a&gt;
        &lt;ul class="push-half--left push-half--bottom"&gt;
          &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="firstSub"&gt;First sub-section&lt;/a&gt; &lt;/li&gt;
          &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="secondSub"&gt;Second sub-section&lt;/a&gt; &lt;/li&gt;
        &lt;/ul&gt;  
      &lt;/li&gt;
      &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="#thirdPart"&gt;…&lt;/a&gt; &lt;/li&gt;
    &lt;/ul&gt;
  &lt;/div&gt;
    </pre>
    
    <hr class="rule rule--ornament" />

    <h3 id="responsivePages">Responsive pages</h3>
    <p>We make our pages responsive (i.e. work nicely at all appropriate screen and window widths) by using floated blocks (or grid items) inside a containing block (or grid). We control the layout using a few fractions plus a couple of keywords.</p>
    <p>We limit the width of text blocks because long lines are more difficult to read.</p>
    <p class="push-half--bottom">If you are familiar with CSS floats, you will find the following straightforward. Even if you have never knowingly met a float before, there are only two rules to remember:</p>
    <ol>
      <li>once a <code>grid</code> is opened, all (direct) child elements of that grid must have the class <code>grid__item</code>
</li>
      <li>use the <code>grid__item</code> class only inside a grid</li>
    </ol>
    <hr class="rule rule--ornament" />

    <h3 id="cssStyleNames">Our CSS class names</h3>
    <p>Our CSS class names use an odd-looking mixture of punctuation! There is a logic to the punctuation, and you can get some useful information from it, once you understand how to decode it.</p>
    <div class="islet islet--bordered"><p><strong>Tech note:</strong> yes, we know the punctuation looks a little like BEM, but it’s not really BEM — and it’s certainly not good BEM — but this is what we have, at least for now. If you have no knowledge of BEM, then simply ignore this note and read on!</p> </div>
    <p>We have classes for parent elements, classes that modify that parent and classes for their child elements.</p>
    <p>A silly example — if <code>run</code> is the name of a parent-class, then <code>run__around</code> could be one of its child-classes. It is a mistake to use <code>run__around</code> if it is not a child of a parent with the class <code>run</code>.</p>
    <p>Further, <code>run</code> could have a different look with a modifier class, say <code>run--fast</code>, or <code>run--slowly</code>.</p>
    <p>The modifier styles used for islands and islets are very useful — there are some examples above in <a href="#emphasis">Adding emphasis</a>.</p>

    <p>Also above, you saw how to adjust the space after a paragraph with the modifier class <code>push-half--bottom</code>.</p>

    <p>Why are there three classes with fractions for the elements with <code>class="grid__item"</code>?  A class like <code>three-fifths</code> works on the widest of screens and windows. Next, <code>lap-one-third</code> sets the width to a third in windows that are less than 1024px wide, overriding the width set by the class <code>three-fifths</code>. Finally, if the window is less than 571px wide, <code>palm-one-whole</code> trumps the fist two classes, making that element as wide as the page.</p>
    
    <div class="islet islet--bordered">
      <p><strong>Tech note:</strong> Yes, it is better to set up CSS to be mobile-first. We know that but we do not have the CSS to do that now — one day …</p>
    </div>

    <hr class="rule rule--ornament" />
    
    <h2 id="waiAria">WAI-ARIA</h2>
    <p>WAI-ARIA (that is, Web Accessibility Initiative — Accessible Rich Internet Applications) is a set of attributes that help screen reader users to understand the structure of a page and move around it. We use only a very small subset of these attributes on Refinery pages. Our pages are being updated to use WAI-ARIA as the opportunity presents.</p>
    <p>We use <code>aria-labelledby="[id of visible label]"</code> to define a label for a <code>nav</code> element, the page contents menu. We also use it to label <code>aside</code> elements, such as a list of related pages.</p>
    <p>If there is no suitable visible label, we could use <code>aria-label="[literal label]"</code> in its place.</p>
    <p>That is all you need to know about ARIA. Except that <em>no</em> ARIA is better than <em>bad</em> ARIA. In other words, do <em>not</em> get creative: use only as described here.</p>
    
    <hr class="rule rule--ornament" />

    <h2 id="avoidTrouble">Avoiding trouble</h2>
    <p>Refinery is rather unforgiving when saving. Although it does try to fix malformed markup, it is not a good fixer. These are some common issues on saving:</p>
    <dl>
      <dt><strong>Closing tags appear in odd places</strong> </dt>
      <dd>If you forget to close an element, Refinery will attempt to close it for you, but the closing tag could be dumped, unhelpfully, as far away as the end of the page.</dd>
      <dd><em>Indenting your HTML (two spaces for each level) is an excellent habit and will help you spot unclosed elements. If you apply markup from the preview pane, the elements will be closed for you.</em> </dd>

      <dt class="push-half--top"><strong>Markup replaced with entities</strong> </dt>
      <dd>If you apply a class from our CSS and forget to close the (keyboard) quotation marks before saving, then chaos ensues! Angle brackets will be replaced with entities and you could have a lot to put right. The same happens if an angle bracket is missing.</dd>
      <dd><em>Keep an eye on what is and is not showing in the preview pane — if text has disappeared, suspect unclosed quotation marks or a missing angle bracket.</em> </dd>

      <dt class="push-half--top"><strong>Refinery will not save the page</strong> </dt>
      <dd>Firstly, Refinery will not save some HTML entities including the vertical ellipsis, the minus sign, the non-breaking hyphen and the letters of the Greek alphabet.</dd>
      <dd class="push-half--top">Secondly, Refinery will not accept a character on the page that is not UTF-8 encoded. If the text you are marking up has been prepared in Windows, for instance, then suspect a character that is outside of the standard alpha-numeric set. I was caught out by what looked like a Latin capital X, but turned out to be a Greek capital ‘chi’. What confused me was that the character looked OK in the preview pane — so beware.</dd>
      <dd class="push-half--top">Thirdly, Refinery will not save raw SVG. If you do not know what SVG is, then that will not be your problem!</dd>
    </dl>

    <hr class="rule rule--ornament" />

    <h2 id="tips">Miscellaneous tips</h2>
    <p>Be wary of trying to convey meaning through anything that relies on sight — for instance, using punctuation to convey meaning. For example, “the places in brackets are the towns and villages covered by each sub-district …” will not be accessible to most screen reader users because the brackets will not be announced.</p>

    <p>Put a space between two consecutive closing tags, such as  <code>&lt;/a&gt; &lt;/li&gt;</code> to stop Refinery from dropping the second tag down to the start of the next line (on saving).</p>

    <p>Do not try to use the <code>br</code> element for anything other than a line break. Block elements have spacing as part of our CSS: if you need a bigger gap than usual after a block element, try <code>class="landmark"</code>.</p>

    <p>Your <strong>browser’s Find command</strong> is your friend — use it in Refinery to find unwanted non-breaking spaces (<code>&amp;nbsp;</code> or <code>&amp;#160;</code>), and hyphens that should be em-dashes, for example. Unfortunately, you cannot find keyboard quotation marks in this way because Find does not distinguish keyboard quotes from curly (typographers’) quotes.</p>
    <p>Your <strong>system or browser spell-checker</strong> is also your friend — make sure it is checking for British (or UK) English spellings and not US English.</p>
    <p>Your browser should have a set of “Developer Tools” that could help you fix a problem. Look under the ‘View’ menu in Chrome or the ‘Tools’ menu in Firefox. You can also open the tools by right-clicking on the mischievous element, then selecting ‘Inspect’.</p>
    <p>Proofreading in the HTML pane is not easy and the preview pane is not the most helpful because it does not use our CSS. Take time out to read the page in a browser — I often find typos that way that I’ve missed in Refinery.</p>
    <p>You will need to check links and responsiveness in a browser. Testing links to other Refinery pages is not so straightforward as you should not make a link to a draft page — leave that task to the person who is responsible for signing off the HTML and CSS. (See <a href="#links">Links, above</a>, for how to signify a link-in-waiting.)</p>
    <p>Refinery deletes HTML comments on saving. If you want to leave a temporary note on a draft page, then use the <code>mark</code> element. It will be hard to overlook when you come to final page checks!</p>
    <hr class="rule rule--ornament" />

    <h2 id="resources">Resources</h2>
    <p>The internet is a great resource, but please weigh up any advice or solutions that you find there in the light of the information in this guide. In particular, so-called advice about accessibility might be out-of-date, misguided or simply wrong. Even respected websites are apt to offer advice that solves an issue for some users (screen reader users, say) at the expense of creating an issue for others (those who cannot use a pointing device, for example).</p>
    <p>If you believe this guide to be wrong on a particular point, please contact your manager or create an issue on ZenHub or GitHub. Thank you.</p>
    <h3>Text editors</h3>
    <p>A ‘basic text-editor’ is included with you computer’s operating system (Notepad on Windows and TextEdit on a Mac): we cannot recommend them for anything beyond search-and-replace of the text, <em>before</em> marking up. If you have a very old version of either, it <em>could</em> be more useful. The more recent versions are really mini word-processors, which limits their usefulness for writing plain text.</p>
    <p>Nowadays we have ‘modern text editors’  and ‘source code editors’. These are great for HTML but as they are powerful pieces of software that can do much more than you will need, the initial learning curve is a bit steep. However, they are well-worth exploring.</p>
    <p class="push-half--bottom">These editors are free to download:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>the easiest to get started with is probably <a href="http://brackets.io/">Brackets</a>. It is available for Windows, Mac and most Linux distributions</li>
      <li>if you are on Windows, a well-established alternative is <a href="https://notepad-plus-plus.org/">Notepad++</a> </li>
    </ul>

     
    
    

   <h3>Online tools</h3>
    <p class="push-half--bottom">You could find these online tools useful, but be aware that they could leave you with work to do:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><a href="https://www.htmlwasher.com/">HTML Washer</a> claims that it “Reduces a HTML document (or fragment) to basic HTML tags and attributes – clean HTML”. It also claims to fix indentation, but it does not.</li>
      <li><a href="https://www.htmlcorrector.com">HTML Corrector</a> advertises that it “Makes a HTML document (or fragment) a valid one”. It will also tidy indentation. But, it returns a complete, valid page, even though you submit a fragment, so be careful what you copy back to Refinery!</li>
    </ul>
    <p>The <a href="https://validator.w3.org/">W3C HTML5 validator</a> expects a full page, but you can paste just your Refinery markup — then ignore anything in the report that does not apply. The validator will find unclosed elements, deprecated markup and more. (You cannot simply give the validator the URL, or address, of your page because the test sites are behind a login.)</p>
    <p>If you’d rather validate a complete page and you have access to a proper text editor, then you can create a minimal file like this:</p>
    <pre>&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;
&lt;html lang="en"&gt;
&lt;head&gt;
  &lt;meta charset="utf-8"&gt;
  &lt;title&gt;Validation checking&lt;/title&gt;
&lt;/head&gt;
&lt;body&gt;

paste Refinery HTML here

&lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;
    </pre>
    <p>You can probably validate such a file from within the text editor. If not, open the W3C validator and upload your minimal file. If there is a scoped <code>style</code> block at the top of the page, you’ll get an error message about it: if the error message bothers you, temporarily comment-out the <code>style</code> block by wrapping it in <code>&lt;!--</code> and <code> --&gt;</code> tags.</p>
    
    <h4>Try using a screen reader</h4>
    <p>Once you know the basics of using a screen reader, you can check your landmark labels and use it to proofread the text. It will help you find typos and some wrong words. You will also hear where a comma would help, or where there is a comma in the wrong place or where a sentence or paragraph is too long.</p>
